[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:AJT82.AK82.Q2.T5 63.JT4.T86.A7632 74.Q73.AKJ73.KJ9 KQ95.965.954.Q84"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\S.  
You respond 2\D, a 2/1 force to game.  Partner rebids 2\h, showing a 4-card side suit.

You don't have 4 \Hs, nor do you have have 3 \Ss. You do, however, have stoppers in \Cs so you bid 2NT. 
South happily says 3NT.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:AJT82.AT82.Q2.K5 96.7654.98.AQJ62 74.KQ3.AKJ73.T97 KQ53.J9.T654.843"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 3C Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{East opens 1\S. How do you respond? 
You bid 2\d, a 2/1 force to game.  East rebids 2\h, showing a 4-card heart suit.   

You don't have 4 \Hs, nor do you have 3 \Ss. Furthermore,  you don't have stoppers in \Cs so you cannot bid NT. Since you have to keep bidding, but have no reasonable bid you can make, you bid the fourth suit, 3\C. Compare this Deal with Deal 21.
East understands that West's \C bid is Fourth-Suit-Forcing, and does not actually show \Cs. However since East does have a \C stopper he bids 3NT. In this case this turns out to be the best game contract.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:T82.A2.A8542.Q85 .JT98.JT96.AK643 AK974.KQ63.73.T7 QJ653.754.KQ.J92"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "2S"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
Pass Pass 1S Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 2S Pass Pass Pass
{North passes - what should you open? 
North now bids 2\D.  
Since North originally passed this is <b>NOT</b> 2/1 Game Force. Instead, it is non-forcing and shows 11 or more points. 
You should show your 4-card \H suit. North gives a preference to 2\S.  What do you do now? 

Knowing that North does not have opening strength you pass 2\S.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:KQT62.A74.84.A85 A98.Q52.QJ93.942 74.9863.A762.KQ3 J53.KJT.KT5.JT76"]
[Declarer "W"]
[Contract "2S"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2S Pass Pass Pass
{West opens 1\S.  
With 9 points and a doubleton \S you must respond 1NT.   Partner rebids 2\c.   

East prefers \C over \S but must allow for the possibility that West has bid a 3-card suit. So East gives a preference to 2\S. This is called a "false preference", but it assures the team of being in at least a 7-card fit. 
West happily passes and the pair lands in a reasonable contract, probably better than 1NT.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:AK874.J86.AJ6.93 52.T53.KQT73.J74 Q6.AKQ972.984.AQ JT93.4.52.KT8652"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4C =1= Pass 4D =2= Pass 4NT =3= Pass 5H =4= Pass 5NT =5= Pass 6H =6= Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:control"]
[Note "2:control"]
[Note "3:keycard ask for \h s"]
[Note "4:2 no Q"]
[Note "5:Specific kings ask"]
[Note "6:none below \H s"]
{How do you start the bidding? 
You opens 1\S. Partner bids 2\H.    
Your priority on your first rebid is to agree trumps if possible. Knowing North has at least a 5-card suit, you raise to 3\H.  You are in a Game Forcing auction, so you know partner will continue bidding.
North now bids 4\c.   [4D]
North's 4\c bid shows first or second round control in clubs, and shows slam interest.  You cooperate by bidding your next control up suit order - 4\d.  This doesn't promise extra values, it's just following partner's path.
North asks for keycards using 1430.  What is your reply? 
You show two keycards without the trump queen.  Partner is excited about this and bids 5NT - what's your bid now? 
Partner's 5NT is asking for specific kings.  Since we don't have any kings lower than the trump suit, we have to bid 6\h.
 and gets two. He decides to find out about Kings, if South happens to have three he will bid 7NT. When South shows just one North settles for 6\H. This should be a good slam, needing only a decent \S break.
}

